  "prompt": "Is it necessary to complete graduation to get the software engineering job at Google?",
  "response": "While having a degree is often beneficial and can make you a more competitive candidate, it is not strictly necessary to complete a formal graduation to get a software engineering job at Google or other major tech companies. Google values skills, experience, and the ability to solve complex problems. They assess candidates through rigorous technical interviews that focus on coding, algorithms, design, and problem-solving skills.\n\nGoogle has hired candidates who are self-taught or have gained skills through coding bootcamps, online courses, or practical experience. However, you would need to demonstrate your proficiency and excellence in coding, problem-solving, and software engineering principles through their interview process, typically consisting of several stages including phone interviews, coding challenges, and on-site interviews.\n\nIt's important to build a solid portfolio of projects and to have a good grasp of the fundamentals of computer science, whether you obtain the knowledge through a degree program or other methods. If you lack formal education, having tangible proof of your skills, such as competing in coding competitions, contributing to open-source projects, or having a strong GitHub repository, can significantly enhance your chances.",
